******
[6] Utah (Cache County): commercial flocks
Date: Sat 23 Apr 2022
Source: Fox 13 Now [edited]
https://www.fox13now.com/news/local-news/udaf-confirms-second-case-of-bird-flu-in-utah


Utah's Department of Agriculture and Food (UDAF) has confirmed a 2nd case of bird flu in Utah.

In a press release sent out Saturday [23 Apr 2022] morning, UDAF announced the highly pathogenic avian influenza was detected in birds on a farm in Cache County.

This comes after the department had detected the virus in a backyard flock of chickens in Utah County on Monday [18 Apr 2022].

The owner of the farm noticed his birds experiencing signs of the virus and immediately contacted UDAF. The farm had been following "very strict biosecurity measures" since the agency's announcement on Monday [18 Apr 2022].

"The diagnosis of HPAI on this farm is devastating," said Dr. Dean Taylor, Utah State Veterinarian, in the press release. "UDAF is working to contain the disease and prevent it from spreading further in this area."

UDAF urges bird owners to continue to check for signs in their birds. Signs include a high death rate among flocks, nasal discharge, decreased appetite or water consumption, and lack of coordination in birds.

Owners whose birds are exhibiting signs are asked to contact the state veterinarian's office immediately by email at<statevet@utah.gov>.

According to the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, there have still been no human cases of this particular strain of HPAI detected in the United States.

[Byline: Stephen Romney]

