[7] Pennsylvania (Lancaster County): commercial flocks
Date: Mon 25 Apr 2022
Source: Successful Farming [edited]
https://www.agriculture.com/news/business/two-more-bird-flu-outbreaks-on-pennsylvania-egg-farms


In less than 3 months, highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) has killed more than 31 million birds, mostly chickens and turkeys, in domestic flocks from the Atlantic coast into the Rockies, according to USDA data released Sunday [24 Apr 2022]. Officials said bird flu was identified on 2 additional egg farms in Lancaster County, Pennsylvania, with a combined 2 million hens.

HPAI was a factor in high egg, chicken, and turkey prices. The USDA said there were 373 million hens in the US laying flock at the start of this month [April 2022], a decline of 5% from April 2021. According to USDA data, 5.4 million laying hens died in outbreaks so far this month [April 2022].

Egg and poultry meat prices are likely to be elevated through the end of the year [2022], Wells Fargo analyst Courtney Schmidt told the Washington Post.

More than 50 million chickens and turkeys died in the 2014-2015 HPAI epidemic, including 12% of the country's laying hens. Some 211 commercial poultry farms were hit during the epidemic, which ended in mid-June 2015.

By comparison, 150 commercial flocks have been infected this year [2022], following the 1st confirmed outbreak on 8 Feb [2022]. HPAI has been identified in 91 commercial flocks during April [2022], compared to 51 flocks in March [2022], but less than half as many birds have died this month [April 2022] compared with March [2022], roughly 9 million vs. 21 million.

[Byline: Chuck Abbott]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[One of the articles listed above did a brief comparison regarding the outbreak in 2004 versus now. The number of birds affected has increased dramatically.

Please, if you have birds whether as a pet, a backyard flock, or a commercial production unit, take extreme safety issues to protect your birds.

Some facilities are limiting the feeding of some poultry houses to only one person, who must not own or work with other birds, even pet birds, in any way. Keeping birds inside is helpful. It is critical to have on clean boots, gloves, and coveralls when entering any poultry house or premises. While there have been no human cases of this influenza strain, it is strongly suggested that any individuals entering a poultry facility/house should have a face covering on to prevent any viral particles from the nose or mouth to reach the birds.

This is not a food safety issue, but it is a food issue, as the fewer birds there are, the fewer eggs and meat products available. The price goes up. So please be extremely diligent in protecting your birds. - Mod.TG

